Telco customer churn prediction :

Customer churn, also known as customer attrition, refers to the phenomenon where customers cease their relationship with a company, either by ending their subscription, discontinuing their service, or switching to a competitor. This model is designed to analyze historical customer data and predict which individuals will be churning . Using a diverse range of featuresour model aims to uncover the underlying factors contributing to customer churn. By training on historical data where churn events are known, our model learns to recognize patterns indicative of potential churn risk.

The histogram plot illustrates the distribution of tenure (the duration of customer subscription) for both churn and non-churn customers .

  • The data is segmented into two groups: churn customers (those who have terminated their subscription) and non-churn customers (those who are still subscribed).
  • For churn customers, the histogram peaks at lower tenure values, indicating that a proportion of churn customers have shorter subscription durations.
  • In contrast, the distribution for non-churn customers is more spread out, with a higher frequency of longer tenure values. This suggests that a larger portion of non-churn customers have been subscribed for an extended period suggesting that strategies to improve customer retention may need to focus on enhancing the early stages of the customer experience..

=> The observed differences in tenure distribution between churn and non-churn customers highlight the importance of tenure as a predictive factor for customer churn.

Train/Test our model :

Decision Tree Classifier :

a decision tree classifier offers several advantages. Firstly, decision trees are intuitive and easy to interpret, making them suitable for explaining the factors that contribute to customer churn. This interpretability is crucial for businesses to understand the underlying patterns driving customer behavior.Additionally, decision trees are robust to outliers and do not require extensive data preprocessing, saving time and effort in the model development process. Furthermore, decision trees can capture non-linear relationships between predictors and the target variable, allowing for more accurate predictions in complex churn scenarios.

  • simplicity, interpretability, and flexibility made decision tree classifier a suitable tool for predicting churn
  • We will be initializing our Decision Tree Classifier and train the model on the training data :
In[]:
df_encoded = pd.get_dummies(df)#encode the categorical data to numerical data so that the model can understand it 


y = df_encoded['Churn'] #target variable that we want to predict
x = df_encoded.drop('Churn', axis=1)

x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

tree_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=4, random_state=42)
tree_clf.fit(x_train, y_train)

x_test.info() #to get the information of the test data

Evaluation of the model using decision tree classifier:

A confusion matrix is a valuable tool for evaluating the performance of a classification model. It provides a comprehensive summary of the model's predictions by comparing them to the actual labels in the test dataset. The matrix is organized into four quadrants: true positives (TP), true negatives (TN), false positives (FP), and false negatives (FN). In the context of churn prediction, true positives represent cases where the model correctly identifies customers who churned, while true negatives denote cases where the model correctly identifies customers who did not churn. On the other hand, false positives occur when the model incorrectly predicts churn for customers who actually did not churn, and false negatives occur when the model incorrectly predicts non-churn for customers who actually churned.

In[]:
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
class_labels = ['Not Churn', 'Churn']

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False , xticklabels=class_labels, yticklabels=class_labels)
plt.xlabel('Predicted Labels')
plt.ylabel('True Labels')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.show()

the goal is to minimize false predictions (both false positives and false negatives) while maximizing true predictions.

The Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve is a graphical representation used to evaluate the performance of a classification model at various classification thresholds. It illustrates the diagnostic ability of a binary classifier system as its discrimination threshold is varied.

we will use the roc curve to evaluate the model which will represents the ability of the model to discriminate between positive and negative classes along with the auc score which is interpreted as the probability that the model will rank a randomly chosen positive example higher than a randomly chosen negative example :

In[]:
y_prob = tree_clf.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1] #predict the probability of the target variable using the test data to get the roc curve
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)
# Plot ROC curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='blue', lw=2, label='ROC curve (AUC = %0.2f)' % auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='gray', linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

Customer churn prediction typically involves binary classification tasks where the model predicts whether a customer will churn (positive class) or not (negative class). The ROC curve provides a comprehensive evaluation of the model's ability to discriminate between churn and non-churn cases by considering various classification thresholds.

the target variable or the positive class in the ROC curve is typically the event of interest, which is "churn" or "customer leaving." This means that the model's performance is evaluated based on its ability to correctly classify customers who churn (true positives)

Hyper-tunning :

The objective of hyperparameter tuning is to optimize the performance of the machine learning model by adjusting these hyperparameters (settings that govern the learning process of the algorithm).This optimization is typically done through a systematic search over a predefined range of hyperparameter values, guided by a performance metric such as accuracy, precision, recall, or the area under the ROC curve (AUC).

We will perform here a Grid search and k-fold cross validation for Decision Tree classifier emphasizing the effect of hyper-parameter tunning on our model's performance :

In[]:
param_grid = {
    'max_depth': [None, 5],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2]
}

# Create a decision tree classifier
tree_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)

# Create GridSearchCV instance
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=tree_clf, param_grid=param_grid, scoring='roc_auc', cv=5, verbose=1)

# Fit the GridSearchCV object to the data
grid_search.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Get the best parameters and best AUC score
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
best_auc = grid_search.best_score_

print("Best parameters:", best_params)
print("Best AUC score:", best_auc)

Fitting 5 folds for each of 8 candidates, totalling 40 fits
Best parameters: {'max_depth': 5, 'min_samples_leaf': 2, 'min_samples_split': 5}
Best AUC score: 0.8298610380040005

there's an 83% chance that the model will correctly predict churn for a randomly selected pair of churned and non-churned customers. This level of predictive performance indicates that the model is effective in identifying potential churners and can be valuable for informing churn prevention strategies.

Random Forest Classifier :

Next, we will be moving to another algorithm known as the Random Forest Classifier; This algorithm is a powerful ensemble learning technique that utilizes multiple decision trees to make predictions. Random Forest can handle large and complex datasets effectively, making it suitable for analyzing customer data from various sources. By aggregating the predictions of multiple decision trees, Random Forest reduces overfitting and provides more robust predictions compared to individual decision trees. This is particularly beneficial in churn prediction, where the goal is to accurately identify customers at risk of leaving the service.

  • We will be initializing our Random Forest Classifier and train the model on the training data and make predictions :
In[]:
rf_clf = RandomForestClassifier(max_depth=4, random_state=42)

y_pred = rf_clf.predict(x_test)

In[]:
y_prob = rf_clf.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1] #predict the probability of the target variable using the test data to get the roc curve
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)
# Plot ROC curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='blue', lw=2, label='ROC curve (AUC = %0.2f)' % auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='gray', linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()

the Decision Tree and Random Forest, exhibit the same AUC score of 0.81, it suggests that they perform similarly in terms of discriminating between positive and negative classes. In other words, both models are equally effective at ranking the instances correctly, distinguishing between churn and non-churn instances. However, it's essential to note that although the AUC scores are the same, the underlying mechanisms of the models differ significantly.

The Random Forest model achieved an improved AUC score of 0.8414 compared to the Decision Tree model's AUC score of 0.8299. This enhancement can be attributed to the ensemble nature of Random Forest. This increased complexity and diversity in the ensemble contribute to capturing more intricate patterns in the data, resulting in better predictive performance as indicated by the higher AUC score .

XGBoost :

XGBoost, short for eXtreme Gradient Boosting, is a powerful machine learning algorithm known for its efficiency and effectiveness in handling structured/tabular data. It utilizes gradient boosting, incorporating regularization techniques,to prevent overfitting while improving generalization. With built-in cross-validation methods and support for custom loss functions, XGBoost offers flexibility and often achieves outstanding performance in predictive modeling tasks.
